<font color="#FF0000">COMMITTMENT WAS (IS?) THE KEY</font><br>
<tt>Fri Oct 17 13:03:37 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I just went out for another cup of coffee.  It's time for me to get some writing on other subjects done, but I cannot.  I am still here, thinking about what's been written in the last few days.  <br><br>
Doc, and you others who were protesting the war, perhaps now that you've seen the level of commitment we had to ourselves, our forces in SEA, perhaps you can begin to grasp the situation when we came home.  We went from this extremely high level of commitment to each other and just hours later were in an environment where nobody wanted to talk to us! When we came back, we were not only on our own (quite literally sometimes), but there was no one to even talk to.  My old girl friend had married several years before, the profs at college were too busy to even say hello, the girls initially wanted nothing to do with anyone from Vietnam (it was kinda taboo to talk about socially), and the feeling of isolation was very great.<br><br>
We had a discussion of stress on another thread, but I think that it ties together with this discussion.  Even now, people cannot begin to appreciate the commitment we had to our mutual survival in SEA; we see no level of commitment sometimes in our society today, and it is hard for us to comprehend why.  <br><br>
So, Class Lass and Doc Spatz, I have a question for you.  Why?  Why don't we see this commitment in general in today's society?  Can this attitude be at the root of some of our society's continuing problems with gangs (young people needing someone who cares), with drugs and alcohol (people too stressed by the dog-eat-dog society to face it anymore), with crime (people whom society has given up on need to make a living somehow), with education (teachers who must now go door-to-door on &quot;fund-raisers&quot; to provide for even small field trips for their students, or music education, or biological supplies, or transportation to a play, or...you get the idea)?  Could it be that this society could use the Vietnam Vet's experience of commitment to revitalize itself?  These are my questions for you.<br>

<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


